Despite that COVID-19 epidemic is ongoing and the data are limited, recent reports indicate that clinical characteristics reported in pregnant women with confirmed SARS-CoV-2 infections are similar to those of non-pregnant women with COVID-19 pneumonia, and no evidence of vertical transmission of SARS-CoV-2 in late pregnancy has been produced so far. Nine studies reported COVID-19 in pregnant women, with a total of 69 patients; however, some of these patients may have been included in more than one study (
 Table 1). The reported cases included five patients in the second trimester of pregnancy, and all other patients were in the third trimester. Most women showed mild or moderate symptoms, and three of them required intensive care. Preterm birth occurred in 8 out of 61 women who gave birth (
